    <p> <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway: }</m> </p>
    <p>  Matrix addition and subtraction help us combine and 
        compare real-life data, making it easier to analyze results and spot patterns.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
            We have two vendors selling apples and oranges over two days.
            The sales data is represented in matrices as follows:
        </p>

        <p>Find A + B and A - B for the matrices below.</p>
        <p>Explain what the results mean in this context.</p>
        <p>
        <m>
          Vendor\ 1: \quad A = \begin{bmatrix} 5 &amp; 7 \\ 3 &amp; 4 \end{bmatrix}
        </m>
        <m>
          Vendor\ 2: \quad B = \begin{bmatrix} 2 &amp; 6 \\ 1 &amp; 5 \end{bmatrix}
        </m>
        </p>
      </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Step 1: Add the matrices:</p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    A + B = \begin{bmatrix} 5+2 &amp; 7+6 \\ 3+1 &amp; 4+5 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 7 &amp; 13 \\ 4 &amp; 9 \end{bmatrix}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>Step 2: Subtract the matrices:</p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    A - B = \begin{bmatrix} 5-2 &amp; 7-6 \\ 3-1 &amp; 4-5 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 &amp; 1 \\ 2 &amp; -1 \end{bmatrix}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>Step 3: Interpret the results.</p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li><m>A + B</m> shows the total number of apples and oranges sold by both vendors each day.</li>
                    <li><m>A - B</m> shows the difference in sales between Vendor 1 and Vendor 2 for each fruit and day. A negative number means Vendor 2 sold more than Vendor 1 for that item.</li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
